replies.bodyText:
Presto does NULLS LAST by default in both directions because we expect that users don't want to see nulls. Consider these queries:
SELECT x FROM t ORDER BY x LIMIT 10;
SELECT x FROM t ORDER BY x DESC LIMIT 10;
In both of these cases, the user likely wants to see some data, not a bunch of nulls. This behavior is allowed by the SQL standard:

If <null ordering> is not specified, then an implementation-defined <null ordering> is implicit. The implementation-defined default for <null ordering> shall not depend on the context outside of <sort specification list>.

